      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Discount Rate ↓ / Growth →</th>
          {sensitivityGrowth.map(g => (
            <th class={Math.abs(g - growthRatePhase1) < 0.001 ? 'current' : ''}>{(g * 100).toFixed(0)}%</th>
          ))}
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {sensitivityTable.map(row => (
          <tr>
            <td>{(row.dr * 100).toFixed(0)}%</td>
            {row.values.map((v, i) => (
              <td class={Math.abs(row.dr - discountRate) < 0.001 && Math.abs(sensitivityGrowth[i] - growthRatePhase1) < 0.001 ? 'current' : ''}>
                ${v}
              </td>
            ))}
          </tr>
        ))}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
  <p>No model is complete. Here's what a DCF inherently misses — and how it might bias our estimate.</p>

  <h3>Upside risks</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Share buybacks:</strong> O'Reilly retires massive amounts of stock every year. Our model uses a static share count. If they continue retiring 4-6% of shares annually, per-share value will compound much faster.</li>
    <li><strong>Store maturity:</strong> Recently opened stores typically take 3-5 years to reach mature profitability. A large cohort of new stores maturing could boost FCF beyond our 8% estimate.</li>
    <li><strong>Commercial growth:</strong> The "Do-It-For-Me" (DIFM) professional segment is growing faster than DIY. Winning more B2B share could accelerate revenue.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>EV Transition:</strong> Electric vehicles have fewer moving parts than internal combustion engines. A rapid shift to EVs could reduce long-term demand for aftermarket parts.</li>
    <li><strong>Debt load:</strong> While manageable, O'Reilly runs with negative working capital and uses debt to fund buybacks. A sustained high interest rate environment could increase their cost of capital.</li>
    <li><strong>Consumer weakness:</strong> While historically recession-resilient (people repair older cars), a severe downturn could defer maintenance spending.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why is the share count so low compared to the price?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">O'Reilly has aggressively bought back its own stock for over a decade. By constantly retiring shares, the ownership stake of remaining shareholders increases, which is why the stock price has compounded so significantly.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>How does the 10-Year Treasury affect this?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">The 10-Year Treasury yield (currently 4.18%) acts as the "risk-free rate." We add an equity risk premium to this to arrive at our 9% discount rate. If rates rise, the discount rate goes up, and intrinsic value falls.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why use an 8% growth rate?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">While revenue may grow slightly slower, O'Reilly consistently expands margins through scale and leverages fixed costs. An 8% FCF growth rate is a conservative estimate that factors in their historical double-digit growth while acknowledging the larger base they are operating from today.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

